Let s \colon  B \to  A and r \colon  A \to  B be a pair of maps. A homotopy h \colon  r\circ  s \sim  1_{B} exhibits s as a section of r and r as a retraction of s. Together, 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen s,r\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 are referred to as a section-retraction pair.

We must check that for every b:B, the fiber of f at b is a proposition. Fixing u_0,u_1:\mathsf {fiber}\,f\,b we must check that u_0=u_1. We let 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen a_0,p_0\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\equiv  u_0 and 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen a_1,p_1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\equiv  u_1 so that we have p_0\colon  fa_0=b and p_1\colon  fa_1=b. Invoking the path object structure on fibers (Example ), it suffices to exhibit the following data:

As f is an embedding, the map \mathsf {act}_{f}\colon  a_0 = a_1 \to  fa_0 = fa_1 has an inverse 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \mathsf {act}_{f}^{-1},\epsilon ,\eta ,\chi \right \rparen \mathclose {}
.

We first define the sections s_{x,y}\colon  fx = fy \to  x = y. Because f is assumed to be propositional, we have by Example  an assignment \phi _{x,y}: \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen h:fx=fy\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen h:fx=fy\right \rparen \mathclose {}
